Generating a detailed image of Elon Musk using only fonts is a complex task. However, I can provide you with an example of embedding a font and displaying some custom-styled text. Here's how you can do it:

First, download a font that you like (for example, "Roboto" from Google Fonts). You can place the downloaded font file in the same directory as your HTML file.

Here's an example HTML code to display styled text using a custom font:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Elon Musk</title>
    <style>
        @font-face {
            font-family: 'CustomFont';
            src: url('Roboto-Regular.ttf');
        }

        .image-text {
            font-family: 'CustomFont', sans-serif;
            font-size: 40px;
            color: #000000;
            text-shadow: 2px 2px 4px #666666;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="image-text">
        Elon Musk
    </div>
</body>
</html>
```

Make sure to replace `'Roboto-Regular.ttf'` with the actual filename of the font you've downloaded. You can adjust the `.image-text` class' properties to change the font size, color, and text shadow according to your preference.

Note that generating a detailed image of Elon Musk using only fonts will require a substantial amount of code and may not yield an accurate representation. This example simply demonstrates how to style text using a custom font.

Certainly! Here's an example of HTML code to create an animated text that says "Breaking News":

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Breaking News Animation</title>
    <style>
        .breaking-news {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            font-size: 30px;
            font-weight: bold;
            text-align: center;
            animation: flicker 1s infinite;
        }

        @keyframes flicker {
            0% {
                opacity: 1;
            }
            50% {
                opacity: 0;
            }
            100% {
                opacity: 1;
            }
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1 class="breaking-news">Breaking News</h1>
</body>
</html>
```

In this code, we use CSS animations (`@keyframes`) to create a flickering effect that alternates the opacity of the text between 0 and 1. The `infinite` keyword ensures that the animation loops indefinitely.

Feel free to adjust the font properties (`font-family`, `font-size`, `font-weight`) and animation properties (duration, timing, etc.) as per your requirements.

To create a simple app, you can use HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. Here's an example of a simple app that allows users to input their name and displays a personalized greeting:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Simple Greeting App</title>
    <style>
        body {
            text-align: center;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }

        input {
            margin: 10px;
            padding: 5px;
        }

        button {
            padding: 10px 20px;
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            color: white;
            border: none;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Simple Greeting App</h1>

    <label for="name">Enter your name:</label>
    <br>
    <input type="text" id="name" placeholder="Your name">
    <br>
    <button onclick="displayGreeting()">Submit</button>

    <h2 id="greeting"></h2>

    <script>
        function displayGreeting() {
            var name = document.getElementById("name").value;
            var greeting = "Hello, " + name + "! Welcome to our simple app.";
            document.getElementById("greeting").textContent = greeting;
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This example app includes an input field where users can enter their name, a submit button, and a greeting message area. When the user clicks the submit button, the `displayGreeting()` function is called, which retrieves the value from the input field, concatenates it with a greeting message, and displays the personalized greeting in the designated area.

You can customize the styles and further enhance the functionality of the app by modifying the HTML, CSS, and JavaScript code.

Creating a full-fledged chat application with GPT (Generative Pre-trained Transformer) language model integration would require significant backend implementation, including server-side code and API integration. However, I can provide a simplified example using HTML and JavaScript to demonstrate how you can create a basic chat-like interface. Note that this example won't include any GPT integration for generating responses. 

Here's the HTML and JavaScript code for a simple chat app interface:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Chat GTP App</title>
    <style>
        body {
            text-align: center;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }

        .chat-container {
            max-width: 400px;
            margin: 0 auto;
            padding: 20px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 10px;
        }

        .chat-message {
            display: flex;
            align-items: flex-start;
            margin-bottom: 10px;
        }

        .message-author {
            font-weight: bold;
            margin-right: 5px;
        }

        .message-content {
            background-color: #f2f2f2;
            padding: 10px;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }

        input[type="text"] {
            width: 100%;
            padding: 10px;
            margin-top: 10px;
        }

        button {
            padding: 10px 20px;
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            color: white;
            border: none;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="chat-container">
        <div class="chat-messages" id="chatMessages">
            <!-- Chat messages will be appended dynamically here -->
        </div>
        <input type="text" id="messageInput" placeholder="Type your message">
        <br>
        <button onclick="sendMessage()">Send</button>
    </div>

    <script>
        function sendMessage() {
            var messageInput = document.getElementById("messageInput");
            var message = messageInput.value;
            messageInput.value = "";

            var chatMessages = document.getElementById("chatMessages");
            var messageElement = document.createElement("div");
            messageElement.className = "chat-message";

            var authorElement = document.createElement("div");
            authorElement.className = "message-author";
            authorElement.textContent = "User:";
            messageElement.appendChild(authorElement);

            var contentElement = document.createElement("div");
            contentElement.className = "message-content";
            contentElement.textContent = message;
            messageElement.appendChild(contentElement);

            chatMessages.appendChild(messageElement);
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example, there is a chat container div that holds all the chat messages. The user can enter their message in the input field, and upon clicking the "Send" button, the `sendMessage()` function will be called. This function appends a new chat message div to the chat container, displaying the user message as "User: [message]".

To integrate GPT for generating responses, you would need to set up a backend server that handles the user input, sends it to the GPT model, and returns the generated response. This involves more advanced programming and API integration, which is beyond the scope of this simple example.

Sure! Here's an example of an HTML calculator:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Calculator</title>
    <style>
        body {
            text-align: center;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }

        .calculator {
            max-width: 300px;
            margin: 0 auto;
            padding: 20px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 10px;
        }

        .calculator input[type="text"] {
            width: 100%;
            padding: 10px;
            margin-bottom: 10px;
        }

        .calculator button {
            width: 50px;
            height: 50px;
            margin: 5px;
            font-size: 18px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="calculator">
        <input type="text" id="result" disabled>
        <br>
        <button onclick="buttonClicked('7')">7</button>
        <button onclick="buttonClicked('8')">8</button>
        <button onclick="buttonClicked('9')">9</button>
        <br>
        <button onclick="buttonClicked('4')">4</button>
        <button onclick="buttonClicked('5')">5</button>
        <button onclick="buttonClicked('6')">6</button>
        <br>
        <button onclick="buttonClicked('1')">1</button>
        <button onclick="buttonClicked('2')">2</button>
        <button onclick="buttonClicked('3')">3</button>
        <br>
        <button onclick="buttonClicked('0')">0</button>
        <button onclick="buttonClicked('+')">+</button>
        <button onclick="buttonClicked('-')">-</button>
        <br>
        <button onclick="buttonClicked('*')">*</button>
        <button onclick="buttonClicked('/')">/</button>
        <button onclick="calculate()">=</button>
        <br>
        <button onclick="clearResult()">Clear</button>
    </div>

    <script>
        function buttonClicked(value) {
            document.getElementById("result").value += value;
        }

        function clearResult() {
            document.getElementById("result").value = '';
        }

        function calculate() {
            var result = document.getElementById("result").value;
            var answer = eval(result);
            document.getElementById("result").value = answer;
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This calculator has a simple layout with a text input field to display the result and buttons for numbers (0-9) and basic arithmetic operators (+, -, *, /). The "Clear" button clears the input field, and the "=" button calculates the expression entered and displays the result.

The JavaScript functions `buttonClicked(value)`, `clearResult()`, and `calculate()` perform the respective functionalities. The `eval()` function is used to evaluate the expression entered in the input field.

Feel free to adjust the styles and expand the functionality of the calculator as per your requirements.

